				\begin{document}$$PCE(\% ) \,=\, \frac{{P_{{{\max }}} \times 100\% }}{{P_{\mathrm{{in}}}}} = \frac{{V_{\mathrm{{oc}}} \times J_{\mathrm{{sc}}} \times FF}}{{P_{\mathrm{{in}}}}} \times 100\%$$\end{document}Whereby, Pmax is the maximal output power of the device under external loads. Open-circuit voltage (Voc) refers to the potential between the two electrodes of the device when the external circuit is open-circuited. Short-circuit current density (Jsc) refers to the current value through the device when the external circuit is short-circuited. Pin is the input power of the device.
